65. consentire suis studiis. These two lines refer of course immediately to those which precede: ‘ If you sympa- thize with his hobby, he will with yours’ ; but the words with which they begin refer back also to v. 39, and so serve to close the period.

66. utroque pollice. In Pliny’s time we learn that ‘premere pollices’ had become a proverb for an expression of favour, N. H. 28. 5. Whether it was so in Horaee’s cannot be said. It was derived apparently from the usage of the amphitheatre, where the people, according to Juv. S. 3. 36, signified their pleasure as to the killing or sparing of a gladiator by turning the thumb one way or other.
